 ab = 01, 10, 11 => (a OR b) = 1\nWhen cd = 10: output = 1 for ab = 01, 10, 11 => (a OR b) = 1\n\nThis suggests that when cd = 00, output = ab (if both a and b are 1)\nFor cd = 10 or 11, output = a OR b\n\nActually, looking at rows:\nRow cd=00: ab=00=>0, ab=01=>0, ab=10=>1, ab=11=>1. So row = 00 -> output = ab \nRow cd=01: ab=00=>0, ab=01=>0, ab=10=>d, ab=11=>d. So row = 01 -> output = 0 (ignore don't cares)\nRow cd=11: ab=00=>0, ab=01=>1, ab=10=>1, ab=11=>1. So row = 11 -> output = a + b\nRow cd=10: ab=00=>0, ab=01=>1, ab=10=>1, ab=11=>1. So row = 10 -> output = a + b\n\nSo, combining:\n- For cd = 00, out = a & b\n- For cd = 01, out = 0\n- For cd = 11, out = a | b\n- For cd = 10, out = a | b\n\nThis simplifies to:\nout = (cd == 2'b00) ? (a & b) : (a | b)\nBut we must consider how to handle the case when cd = 01. It seems all entries are 0, so we could set out = (cd == 2'b00) ? (a & b) : ((cd == 2'b01) ? 1'b0 : (a | b))\nHowever, in practice, since we are working with a simplified truth table, let's consider another way:\n\nFrom a different viewpoint: The output is 1 when:\n- cd = 00, ab = 10 or 11\n- cd = 11, ab = 01 or 10 or 11\n- cd = 10, ab = 01 or 10 or 11\n\nThat gives us:\n- cd=00 and (a=1 and b=1)\n- cd=11 and (a=0 and b=1) or (a=1 and b=0) or (a=1 and b=1) = cd*(a+b)\n- cd=10 and (a=0 and b=1) or (a=1 and b=0) or (a=1 and b=1) = cd*(a+b)\n\nSimplifying further:\noutput = (cd == 2'b00) ? (a & b) : (a | b)\n\nBut this doesn't work because when cd=11 or cd=10, we also get 1 for ab=01, 10, 11. \n\nBetter grouping: \nWe know from K-map that: output=1 for:\n\n- cd = 00, ab = 10 or 11 -> a=1, b=1 or 01 -> a & b\n- cd = 11, ab = 01, 10, 11 -> (a=0,b=1) or (a=1,b=0) or (a=1,b=1) -> a OR b\n- cd = 10, ab = 01, 10, 11 -> (a=0,b=1) or (a=1,b=0) or (a=1,b=1) -> a OR b\n\nSo we realize: output = 1 whenever:\n1. (cd = 00) AND (a = 1 AND b = 1)\n2. (cd = 11) AND (a OR b = 1)\n3. (cd = 10) AND (a OR b = 1)\n\nThis gives us a simpler expression:\n\nLet's try: output = (cd == 2'b00) ? (a & b) : (a | b)\n\nIf cd == 00 -> output = a & b\nIf cd == 11 -> output = a | b\nIf cd == 10 -> output = a | b\n\nNow let's double check against our truth table:\n- cd=00, ab=00 -> output = 0 & 0 = 0 ✓ \n- cd=00, ab=01 -> output = 0 & 1 = 0 ✓ \n- cd=00, ab=10 -> output = 1 & 0 = 0 ✗ But expected was 1.\n\nSo our assumption is wrong. Let's look again.\n\nThe correct minterms:\n- ab=10, cd=00 -> output = 1\n- ab=11, cd=00 -> output = 1\n- ab=01, cd=11 -> output = 1\n- ab=10, cd=11 -> output = 1\n- ab=11, cd=11 -> output = 1\n- ab=01, cd=10 -> output = 1\n- ab=10, cd=10 -> output = 1\n- ab=11, cd=10 -> output = 1\n\nSo we have 1s for:\n- cd=00, ab=10,11\n- cd=11, ab=01,10,11\n- cd=10, ab=01,10,11\n\nThe simplest way to express is using SOP form. But it's easier to just implement:\noutput = (a&b) | (c&d) | (c&~d) | (~c&d) | (a|b|~c|~d)\nNo, this is incorrect too. Let's try writing the Boolean algebra correctly:\n\nLet’s go through each combination:\n1. cd=00, ab=00 -> 0\n2. cd=00, ab=01 -> 0\n3. cd=00, ab=10 -> 1\n4. cd=00, ab=11 -> 1\n5. cd=01, ab=00 -> 0\n6. cd=01, ab=01 -> 0\n7. cd=01, ab=10 -> d (ignore)\n8. cd=01, ab=11 -> d (ignore)\n9. cd=11, ab=00 -> 0\n10. cd=11, ab=01 -> 1\n11. cd=11, ab=10 -> 1\n12. cd=11, ab=11 -> 1\n13. cd=10, ab=00 -> 0\n14. cd=10, ab=01 -> 1\n15. cd=10, ab=10 -> 1\n16. cd=10, ab=11 -> 1\n\nSo output = 1 when:\n- cd=00 AND (ab=10 OR ab=11) -> cd & (a & b | a & ~b) -> cd & a\n- cd=11 AND (ab=01 OR ab=10 OR ab=11) -> cd & (a | b)\n- cd=10 AND (ab=01 OR ab=10 OR ab=11) -> cd & (a | b)\n\nThus:\noutput = cd & a + cd & (a | b) + cd & (a | b) = cd & a + cd & (a | b) = cd & (a + a | b) = cd & (a | b)\nWait, that's wrong again.\n\nLet's take it step by step:\noutput = (cd == 00) ? (a & b) : (cd == 01) ? 0 : (cd == 11) ? (a | b) : (a | b) = (cd == 00) ? (a & b) : (a | b)\n\nLet's just try to verify if a simple expression like (a | b) works:\nIf output = a | b\n1. cd=00, ab=00 -> 0|0 = 0 ✓\n2. cd=00, ab=01 -> 0|1 = 1 ✗ Should be 0\n3. cd=00, ab=10 -> 1|0 = 1 ✗ Should be 1 ✓\n4. cd=00, ab=11 -> 1|1 = 1 ✓\n5. cd=01, ab=00 -> 0|0 = 0 ✓\n6. cd=01, ab=01 -> 0|1 = 1 ✗ Should be 0\n7. cd=01, ab=10 -> 1|0 = 1 ✗ Should be d, which we ignore\n8. cd=01, ab=11 -> 1|1 = 1 ✗ Should be d, which we ignore\n9. cd=11, ab=00 -> 0|0 = 0 ✓\n10. cd=11, ab=01 -> 0|1 = 1 ✓\n11. cd=11, ab=10 -> 1|0 = 1 ✓\n12. cd=11, ab=11 -> 1|1 = 1 ✓\n13. cd=10, ab=00 -> 0|0 = 0 ✓\n14. cd=10, ab=01 -> 0|1 = 1 ✓\n15. cd=10, ab=10 -> 1|0 = 1 ✓\n16. cd=10, ab=11 -> 1|1 = 1 ✓\n\nOnly 2 mismatches at cases 2 and 6. That's not matching exactly what we want.\n\nNow let's think of a better way to write it. Looking at the correct values:\nLet's build the expression using a more direct method.\n\nUsing the full SOP:\nWe have output = 1 for:\n- cd=00, ab=10\n- cd=00, ab=11\n- cd=11, ab=01\n- cd=11, ab=10\n- cd=11, ab=11\n- cd=10, ab=01\n- cd=10, ab=10\n- cd=10, ab=11\n\nThese correspond to minterms:\n- a=1,b=0,c=0,d=0\n- a=1,b=1,c=0,d=0\n- a=0,b=1,c=1,d=0\n- a=1,b=0,c=1,d=0\n- a=1,b=1,c=1,d=0\n- a=0,b=1,c=1,d=1\n- a=1,b=0,c=1,d=1\n- a=1,b=1,c=1,d=1\n\nLet’s derive the function:\nFor c=0, d=0, we get 1 when a=1,b=0 or a=1,b=1\nSo a & b | a & ~b = a\nFor c=1, d=0, we get 1 when a=0,b=1 or a=1,b=0 or a=1,b=1\nSo ~a & b | a & ~b | a & b = b | a & b = b + a & b = b + a = a | b\nFor c=1, d=1, we get 1 when a=0,b=1 or a=1,b=0 or a=1,b=1\nSame as above: a | b\n\nSo it seems like:\nIf c=0, d=0 → output = a\nIf c=1, d=0 → output = a | b\nIf c=1, d=1 → output = a | b\n\nHence, output = c & d ? (a | b) : a\nOr, output = (~c | ~d) ? a : (a | b)\nBut not quite right yet.\n\nLet me re-examine the truth table more carefully:\nWe want output = 1 for:\n- cd = 00, ab = 10 -> (a & b) = 0, but we want 1 (So we're off by one condition).\n- cd = 00, ab = 11 -> (a & b) = 1 ✓ \n- cd = 11, ab = 01 -> (a | b) = 1 ✓ \n- cd = 11, ab = 10 -> (a | b) = 1 ✓ \n- cd = 11, ab = 11 -> (a | b) = 1 ✓ \n- cd = 10, ab = 01 -> (a | b) = 1 ✓ \n- cd = 10, ab = 10 -> (a | b) = 1 ✓ \n- cd = 10